text: People are split on this trailer's tone shift. This is the way I see it; when you break down this concept, it's can seem really goofy & at the same time be scary & I like that it looks like they are going to take it a little serious but also have some goofy/cheesy stuff in the film. When looking at the goofy & scary concept, I don't want this film to try to take itself too serious. I want it to come in & know what type of film it is & play up to it. I don't look at this film & expect it to be a great film or be the next Jaws, even though some have called it to be Jaws for the next generation, I don't see it like that. My expectations on it being great are low. I'm just looking for a fun & entertaining monster movie. I do hope that the film has a mixture of both humor & horror. I don't want the film to have more of one & less of the other. I want the mixture. They can mix well if you do it right. I want it to kinda be like Deep Blue Sea. Say what you want, but that movie was goofy & cheesy but at the same time, it was entertaining. As long as this film can be an entertaining monster flick then I'll be fine with it. I don't want the film to take it self too serious to the point where you can't have fun with it.  EDIT: Also a movie trailer can be edited to look completely different from the actual movie. If nobody has watched it yet, go watch the international version of this trailer. If you liked the first half of this trailer with the serious tone then you will probably like it better. https://youtu.be/w_06KCv96Ns

text: Honestly, as a huge fan of the book series since my high school days, I like what I'm seeing so far, but I'm also a little hesitant. Everyone knows when books are translated to film, there will inevitably be some changes made to condense a few hundred page novel to a two and a half hour movie, that's just the way the industry is. But I'm really hoping that they haven't drastically altered the storyline. Without spoiling the book plot for anyone who hasn't read them yet or risk saying what may spoil the film's possible story, the first book has some pivotal characters, such as Jonas Taylor's (Statham's character) estranged wife Maggie and DJ among others, who push the plot forward, and lead to several major character's deaths which act as the catalyst for the story's climax, which, if they stuck to, that is going to be amazing to see on screen, I gotta say. And I hope they didn't change the ending either, which literally serves as the jump to the sequels (Hint, hint, fellow fans. Angel. All I've gotta say) But I'm going to keep a cautious optimism for this movie, since it's taken over a decade at least to finally be released. But I hope they didn't change or alter too much of the story. And one thing: please, for the love of GOD, don't let them have watered this down to a PG-13 rating just so they can profit from the teenage demographic. This needs a well deserved R rating to do Steve Alten's work justice.

text: Can I just say, that first seen where the meg slowly swims up the girl then stops, IS SCIENTIFICALLY IMPOSSIBLE! Sharks like great white and makos, which are the closest relatives to the megalodon (closest relative is the mako believe it or not) Sharks like that need to constantly be swimming in order to keep oxygen running threw their gills, if they slow, they will be out of breath soon, if they completely stop, they would die (over a period of time not right away of course). It‚Äôd be like someone closing your nose and mouth extremely tight, just think about that.  Also, sharks wouldn‚Äôt even think about stopping like that! A shark would almost always ambush from below (mainly great whites), so that way they can go undetected and can catch their prey of guard.  So there you have it, this movie is already messing up in a 2 MINUTE TRAILER

text: :/ I'm sure it will be at least an okay movie but I'm a bit annoyed that Hollywood is still making movies that demonize sharks. Many species of shark are endangered and few people show sympathy for them. Take for example the grey nurse shark which is harmless to humans, people will still kill this beautiful animal despite it being harmless because people see the fin and think "maneater". The idea of the movie is ridiculous because if an animal that large had remained undetected for so long obviously it would be uninterested in doing what is shown in this trailer, if it were this agressive it would have been found and killed long ago. I feel like ingraining this kind of hate for sharks is a big part of why there isn't as much effort to protect and save sharks as there is for other animal of similar rarity and endangerment.

text: I've been following this movie for a while and I'm totally going to be there opening night no matter what, but I feel like for a very first trailer they should have taken a more serious/darker tone. The first half looked decent, but as soon as that scene with the dog and the hokey music started it genuinely looked like one of those straight to DVD B-movies (albeit one with really good CGI) and I'm not sure that was the best first impression. Don't get me wrong, there is a certain fan base for those kind of movies, but with a $150 mil budget, you'd think you'd want to appeal to the masses, not just B-movie fans. With so much money on the line, it was an odd choice to go that route.

text: video was too long. Halfway through it, I got hungry so I left it playing and went to the kitchen to fix my self a sandwich. But then I found out that I'm out of mayonnaise so I went to a store. There, I saw the most beautiful woman I have ever seen in my whole life. But I'm really a shy person so I took up a three-year personality development course so I can introduce my self. She was very friendly and all, but unfortunately, she has a boyfriend. So I said, all good, I'm a mature person. I want the best for her and I harbor no illusion that I am the best person for her and she seems happy with her boyfriend, so I did not bother her anymore. But we kept in touch and we became friends and I got over my crush on her. Then she broke up with her boyfriend, we drank some alcohol because of it, I told her she'll be fine and I wished her well. I still think she's the most beautiful woman in the world, but like I said, I am over my crush on her. It was like five years already when I first saw her. Besides, I am quiet happy with the friendship I developed with her. It was more important than a crush. So we kept hanging out, drinking, having coffee, and all. I had a girlfriend, she started dating other guys. My girlfriend wants to live some other life without me in it, so I said, okay, I want the best for you and I want you to pursue your happiness. My lady friend and I drank alcohol about it, and she gave me the same advice I gave her when she was in that position and I became okay with the breakup immediately. But we were really drunk, so she spent the night in my apartment. I only have one bed, so you know what that means: She took the bed and I slept on the couch. But on the couch, I really can't sleep. Something was bothering me. So I tossed and turned for about three hours, then I finally can't take it anymore, I stood up and went straight to my room where she's sleeping. I approached the bed, gently sat on it and I reached for her shoulder to pull her closer to me. She stirred and woke up. She asked what's up. I told her, you know, the first time I saw you, I was watching a video and left it playing to get my self a sandwich then went to the store to get some mayo then I got distracted by life that I forgot to finish the video. She said, you know what, I've been wondering about a weird noise in your night drawer. So we opened that drawer, and lo and behold, there's my phone and this video still has two minutes of play time on it.

text: The closest thing to a Megalodon alive today is the Great White shark. It is impossible to hold these things in captivity, partly because as they get bigger, so does their prey. An adult Great White preys on manatees, dolphins and small whales; a little fish now and then won't cut it anymore.   Megalodons were estimated to grow to roughly THREE times the size of Great Whites and preyed on WHALES. A bunch of swimmers, especially child size ones, are not going to cut it for a Megalodon any more than small fish would for a Great White.

text: In 2017 some 18,000 previously unknown species were identified. One was a dolphin, another an orangutan. Others first found in the 70's or later include a horse, pig, deer, zebra, ape, whale and a species of hammerhead shark. Tales of the giant squid floated since the late 1800's but no photographic proof existed until 2004. The Megamouth shark, similar to basking and whale sharks, growing to some 20 geet, was only discovered in the 1970's and since then less than 100 have been observed in the wild. Given how little we know about the Earth, esp. the oceans, it is possible that this species still exists down deep. There are certainly animals still around large enough to be sufficient prey including the largest ever blue whale. We all know about all the old arctic whaling stations so is it possible the whales went there because the waters were too cold for the Meg to follow? Whales are warm-blooded mammals, fish are not.

text: What I like about this is how accurate the dimensions of the Meg are based on current fossil evidence. And that before it starts going after people, it hunts a colossal squid, which would be a probable food source since Sperm Whales, which are about the same estimated size as Meg, hunt such creatures as a part of their diet. They even base a part of its behavior on what modern sharks do at the beginning scene, where though it may have been looking like it was going after the girl, it was actually doing a test bite to see if the facility was edible, deemed it not being so, and left it alone. While it appears to be a typical killer Shark movie for the rest of the trailer, the beginning til the 1:21 Mark does a good job at portraying this shark as a living animal, and not just a movie monster (even though, for the most part, it is.)

text: Okay, the fact that that monster is not something that we humans have come up with, a super-sized great white that just kills people left and right, but is something that actually existed back in the day, is fucking terrifying! Nothing that big should have existed ever, least of all in the ocean!   Still, I am getting sick of these movies about sharks being depicted as mindless, bloodthirsty killers that attack humans all the time. And as much as I thought Jaws was a fun movie, it really rubs me the wrong way that people still use the shark as a monster in so many movies, even today. Especially considering how many sharks humans kill every year compared to how many shark attacks happen in the same year.   But, at least it‚Äôs not a Great White but a Megalodon this time, which is the ancestor of the Great White... um, progress?

text: ...Sorry but I rather this concept would have been done as a squeal to the JAWS franchise by Mr. Spielberg... at least it would of kept the intensity the MEG deserves.. If I had made this film, I rather see Huge Jackman in the leading role. The story would be about a family fishing trip gone wrong as his wife an kids go missing, and never seen again. This tragic event happens while he was commanding secret Navy Seal missions overseas. He rushes back only to return to a shattered life and home. Its 2am the last stages of depression start to set in, his hand shaking while reaching for his firearm .. He sits in his bedroom, dark and silhouetted by a TV ambience. He begins grinding his pistol into his temple cursing himself for the fact of not being there to protect his family.. He takes his last breath and slowly pulls the trigger. This is a BREAKING NEWS REPORT!!! .. He slowly turns his head as sweat drips from his nose... Anchor: Good evening, we have just received word that yet another family boating disaster has occurred. This happens in the same area, but this time there are still remains of the boat to be seen by the news helicopter spotlights. The dark ocean waters reveal what looks to be a rather large white yacht missing its rear half. The reporter ends the report with comments leading to what looks like some kind of unexplained animal attack. With this report, Hugh Jackman's mission of revenge begins. Buckle Up as he seeks revenge on a underestimated foe of our ocean's deep dark history.  Search the movie PRISONERS to see Jackman's role I'm referring to.

text: WTF?! I've been waiting for this movie for 10 yrs... or 15 maybe? It was optioned forever ago. Anyway, I'm already not liking what I see.   (1) Judging by this shitty trailer, it appears the studio not only took the science interwoven throughout the book out of the movie, but also took the damn book out of it altogether. The entire appeal of the MEG series is the fact we don't know (yet) what lays in the deepest trenches of the ocean, but we do know it's likely luminescent. The author's meticulous scientific details were obviously not employed on even a rudimentary level; the damn shark isn't white much less glowing! Frankly, it looks like a giant turd with teeth.   (2) Whatever "genius" writer decided to compile a brilliant series into 1 movie truly did a disservice to MEG fans. Why did you bother naming it MEG when you went straight to book 2, The Trench? And even then you still didn't stick to the book! It's as if you took bits from MEG and pieces from The Trench and Frankensteined the shit out of them.   (3) I hope that "music" is not the score.  Studios really need to stop turning books into movies because you end up disappointing fans every time. You'll spend a jillion dollars making another tired superhero movie, but utterly ruin brilliant science fiction that could have appealed to ALL demographics and not just 12-year-old boys. With the exception of Get Out, I can't remember the last time I paid to see a film, but MEG won't be the one that gets me into the theater. Hell, I won't even bother borrowing the screener because I have zero desire to see such a suspenseful series turned into "Sharknado 7: The Big Turd With Teeth."

text: My honest review of the Meg, I went and saw it and paid almost $20 for my ticket:  Movie overall was a 3/10 whereas Altens books are 1/10 and maybe at best a 2/10. You can tell the movie was filmed in a giant pool for most scenes. The CGI was not the best , but it was the best it could be for a B movie shark flick, however this was not a cheap B movie it was an expensive $150 million dollar flop. Deep blue sea is by far better as is the original Jaws. If they used animatronics for this movie you would probably be looking at a $500 million dollar budget. The story line was stupid but it has some very nice scenes and funny punch lines. Megalodon was 70-90 feet? Megalodon feared nothing? Hahaha Only 2 references made to the Killer whales, the creatures responsible in part for megalodon extinction. It went to the primordial sea but couldn't find tropical waters?¬† Save your money and wait until it comes to Netflix or some other streaming service. I wasted almost 2 hours and almost$20 dollars, hopefully other people don't have to.

text: ‚ÄãFrom Digg... "The Meg," which stars Jason Statham and an 80-foot CGI megalodon shark is in theaters today. It's not particularly good. And while the reviews aren't as universally bad as they were for "Gotti" or "The Emoji Movie", the bad reviews are delightfully harsh. We've gathered the snarkiest snippets below:      "How do you make a blockbuster movie starring a superhuman action star and a giant prehistoric monster that's so deadly dull?" [Rolling Stone]      "'The Meg' is a one hundred percent inorganic meal, something made from pre-tasted and then regurgitated ingredients." [Hollywood Reporter]      "Just observing that 'The Meg' is a dead, lifeless film is easy. All you have to do is sit there and watch for 10 minutes, any 10 minutes." [SFGate]      "Of all the thrillers made about tender, juicy humans splashing away from ravenous giant sharks, 'The Meg' is undeniably the most recent." [NPR]       "[S]harks deserve better than this." [IndieWire]      "It is neither dumb nor smart enough to be fun, and spends way too much time with its boring human characters when it could be spending it with, you know, the giant shark." [Vulture]      "The great thing about 'Jaws' (sorry) is that its tone is so elastic, moving from humor to horror to exhilaration to parody to tenderness; I'd say that the Good-Bad thing about 'Deep Blue Sea' (Im sorry. Im trying to remove it) is that it at least toggles between camp and carnage. 'The Meg' doesn't have a variable or inconsistent tone‚Ää ‚Äî ‚Ääit has no tone at all." [The Ringer]      "It's not fun, it's not serious, it's not scary. It is stupid." [New York Post]      "'The Meg' lacks the imagination to be shameless." [Variety]      "'The Meg' is lackadaisically paced, dull to look at, and has trouble keeping track of space and plot (it's never clear what Mana One does), but it's always very clear on what kind of expensive watches the characters are wearing... Whoever negotiated the placement of those watches got their money's worth. You won't." [AV Club]      "Apparently constructed under the assumption that moviegoers' I.Q. drops precipitously during the summer months." [New York Times]

text: I think its funny how many of the critics are saying it should be like "Piranha 3-D" or "Sharknado". Yea. Sure. Like THOSE weren't universally panned by critics. So from what I gather,  the critics bashing the film think its either not bad enough (To you I say: Just watch Syfy channel, no need to ruin OUR big budget shark movies, we like them at least partially not retarded, thank you very much) or they are taking it too seriously (To you I say: What did you expect? Citizen Kane?  Its a giant fucking shark movie, suspend your disbelief, fuck) Alot of these bad reviews seem to be nothing but hollow points from these "film critics". Its a fun shark movie, nothing more, nothing less, you dont have to like it, but if you are going to critique it ACTUALLY CRITIQUE IT.   Theres plenty of legit things to critisize in the movie, but all the critics best arguments seem to be "Needs more blood and cheese" or "Its a shark movie, therefore it must be at least as bad as Sharknado for it to be any good" or "You expect me to believe this shit?" Yet they will suspend their disbelief for Marvel movies, Jurassic World Kong, ect. Ect. All of which have as little or less plot substance than The Meg.  Fucking ametures. I miss Siskel and Ebert. Theres a reason Piranha 3-D flopped and Sharknado is a tv only movie. They arent good. Plain and simple. They are not even fun, and NO movie, I REPEAT: NO MOVIE should try to imitate either of them.

Mosasaurus: Mosasaurus hoffmannii, the largest known species, may have reached up to 17 m (56 ft) in length  ¬†(source wikipedia)   but with further research i found that the Mosasaurus had a long, thin body with jaws designed more for feeding on smaller prey such as ammonites and fish ...   the Megalodon instead had a much more robust body and huge jaws built for devouring whales and other large marine mammals. A Mosasaurus would not have been able to get its jaws around the much thicker body of the Megalodon. It would just take one catastrophic bite for the Megalodon to end the battle. In addition the Mosasaur‚Äôs body type would have been inefficient for high-speed swimming giving the Megalodon another huge advantage in maneverablity.  ¬†https://www.fossilera.com/blog/megalodon-vs-mosasaurs-who-would-win
